<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/from_our_own_correspondent/2664985.stm">news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world...664985.stm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&quot;The congregation has only been in this massive building for just over four years - but already is threatening to outgrow it. A total of 18,000 people come here for the three services every weekend. <br>
<br>
Many thousands more spend a good chunk of their week in the smart new gymnasium, food court, day-care centre, classrooms... You see this is not just a church, it is the shopping mall of modern religion - a new medieval city, clustered round the sanctuary. <br>
<br>
One of the other Mega-Churches is actually introducing a McDonalds. Some of them have housing developments on campus, one is building a religious theme park based on the story of Jonah and the whale.&quot; <br>
<br>
-----The above is just down right weird to me...but a very easy way to lure people to the church I guess....<br>
<br>
&quot;One religious affairs expert described it as a form of Christian cocooning - as the faithful withdraw from what they see as an increasingly threatening world.&quot;<br>
<br>
------This sounds quite feasible - I could imagine some of the fundies I know online reacting very well to a prospect like that. <br>
<br>
&quot;Another former member of the congregation explained to us a less high-minded motivation. Southeast Christian is the place to be seen in Louisville, it's the place to meet the leading local politicians, to make business contacts. It's the country club of religion.&quot;<br>
<br>
------But the above paragraph is just down right scary!!!!!<br>
<br>
Maybe it is just coming from GB that makes it all seem wierd to me...becuase religion isn't really &quot;out there&quot; like it seems to be in USA - but this whole &quot;megachurch&quot; thing strikes me as really creepy!! *shrug*<br>
<br>
Anyway..like I said...anyone here ever been to one of these places? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.growthspurts.com/drivee/images/434360233606.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gaia25>Gaia25</A> at: 1/18/03 1:32:40 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=filfilksq>filfilksq</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/18/03 4:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=78.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Megachurches</span><hr size=1> I grew up in Louisville.. haven't lived there for over a decade, but the 'rents still do so I visit there every so often.<br>
<br>
Last time I was actually living there the big church mentioned in your last quote was just getting underway.  It was totally out of control -- they had just moved into this enormous facility, and already it was too small for them.<br>
<br>
I guess I could care less on one level, what worries me more is the extended effect this could have.  For example, at the time I was working in a fast-growing home health care org, and all the bigwigs from the company went to that church.  It would bother me if I thought that there were groups of execs going to the church, and deciding company issues either at the church or being influenced by people there.. or worse, people feeling pressured to join the church just to stay with the &quot;in crowd&quot; at work.<br>
<br>
I guess it's the same principle of the whole Augusta National thing.. I could care less whether or not they want women in their little club.. it only bothers me if they are doing all these big deals inside and thereby are excluding others from important business/government issues. Something similar happened at another place I worked (this time in Chicago).  All the big players were smokers, and they'd all go to take smoke breaks together outside.  One guy decided he wanted to quit smoking, but felt forced to keep going outside with everyone else on smoke breaks because they'd chat about business and sometimes even make business decisions out there.  Don't know if he was able to stick with stopping smoking, but I felt bad he was put in that position anyway.<br>
<br>
Did I make any sense?<br>
<br>
Kate <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 159<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/18/03 5:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=78.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Megachurches</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Did I make any sense?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
